¹5 f. The example of Circe is well chosen. The poet prays that Canidia like the early sorceress will reverse her spell. —saetosaz i-e. with swinish bristles.—duris pellibus ε abl. with exuere. -labori- osi: Homeric πολύτλας, πολυτλή- μων; best taken with Ulixei. still, cf. 16, 60.

17 f. mens: Horace supposes that Circe's victims lost their minds as well as shapes, but in the Ho- meric account their fate is made the more pathetic because their wits remain. — sonus : voice.— honor : in contrast to the ugly swinish faces they had just put off.
